An overview of modern mathematical physics, through the lens of pure mathematics, will be presented. We discuss various ideas originally stemming from physical considerations and how they pertain to various areas of math, such as algebra, geometry, and analysis. The discussion will also include some open projects in the mathematical physics community.

The purpose of this presentation is to show how physical ideas seem to abound throughout mathematics and, as suggested by the title, to show that many problems in mathematical physics can be explored by pure mathematicians.

Some familiarity with group theory will be assumed in this presentation. 
